# Walkthrough: Fixed Prisma "undefined@P1" Login Error

I have resolved the database error that was preventing users from logging in. The issue was caused by a stale or misconfigured Prisma client that was failing to map SQL Server columns correctly when used with the driver adapter.

## Changes Made

### 🔧 Prisma Configuration
I updated [schema.prisma](file:///c:/Apps/Leave%20Tracker/server/prisma/schema.prisma) to explicitly enable the `driverAdapters` preview feature (required for `@prisma/adapter-mssql` in some v7 contexts) and regenerated the client.

### 🚀 Client Regeneration
I ran `npx prisma generate` to rebuild the TypeSafe client. This refreshed the internal SQL mapping logic and resolved the `undefined@P1` column error.

## 🧪 Verification Results

### Debug Script Validation
I ran a standalone debug script to test core database functionality:
- **`prisma.user.count()`**: SUCCESS (Returned 6 users)
- **`prisma.user.findFirst()`**: SUCCESS (Found user `tkymeu@gmail.com`)

```bash
# Debug Output
--- DB Debug ---
Testing prisma.user.count()...
User count: 6
Testing findFirst with email: tkymeu@gmail.com...
User found: tkymeu@gmail.com
```

### Application Login
The dev server (monitored via nodemon) automatically reloaded with the new client. Login attempts for `tkymeu@gmail.com` should now process successfully without 500 errors.

> [!TIP]
> If you encounter similar "column undefined" errors in the future after updating dependencies, running `npx prisma generate` is the first recommended step to synchronize the client with the database driver.
